<article>
    <h1>Repub&#xAD;li&#xAD;can se&#xAD;na&#xAD;tor slams ef&#xAD;fort to chal&#xAD;lenge elec&#xAD;tion re&#xAD;sults as a &#x2018;dan&#xAD;ger&#xAD;ous ploy&#x2019;</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20210102/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2021-01-02"><time>2021-01-02</time></a>
        - <span>WORLD</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>WASH­ING­TON • Se­na­tor Ben Sasse has con­demned a drive by his Repub­li­can col­leagues in Congress to chal­lenge the re­sults of the 2020 elec­tion, re­buk­ing the ef­fort as a “dan­ger­ous ploy” led by law­mak­ers who are “play­ing with fire”.</p>
    <p>In a blis­ter­ing open let­ter to his con­stituents on Thurs­day, Mr Sasse of Ne­braska be­came the first Repub­li­can se­na­tor to pub­licly con­demn a de­ci­sion by Se­na­tor Josh Haw­ley to chal­lenge Pres­i­den­t­elect Joe Bi­den’s vic­tory, say­ing it was in­tended to “dis­en­fran­chise mil­lions of Amer­i­cans”.</p>
    <p>“Let’s be clear what is hap­pen­ing here: We have a bunch of am­bi­tious politi­cians who think there’s a quick way to tap into the Pres­i­dent’s pop­ulist base with­out do­ing any real, long-term dam­age,” Mr Sasse wrote. “But they’re wrong – and this is­sue is big­ger than any­one’s per­sonal am­bi­tions. Adults don’t point a loaded gun at the heart of le­git­i­mate self-govern­ment.”</p>
    <p>Mr Sasse’s scathing re­marks came a day af­ter Mr Haw­ley of Mis­souri an­nounced that he would be ob­ject­ing to Congress’ cer­ti­fi­ca­tion of the Elec­toral Col­lege re­sults on Jan 6, the fi­nal pro­ce­dural step in af­firm­ing Mr Bi­den’s vic­tory.</p>
    <p>Mr Haw­ley’s move en­sures that the process, usu­ally a for­mal­ity, will force up-or-down votes on the House and Se­nate floors, re­quir­ing law­mak­ers to ei­ther show loy­alty to Pres­i­dent Don­ald Trump and ob­ject to the re­sults or pro­tect the sanc­tity of the elec­toral process.</p>
    <p>There is al­most no chance that the ef­fort, led by Mr Haw­ley in the Se­nate and a small group of Repub­li­can law­mak­ers in the House, will suc­ceed in re­vers­ing the out­come of the elec­tion. But Mr Haw­ley’s de­ci­sion to chal­lenge the re­sults is forc­ing a test of how far the Repub­li­can Party is will­ing to go to back</p>
    <p>Mr Trump’s false claims.</p>
    <p>Se­nate Ma­jor­ity Leader Mitch McCon­nell has dis­cour­aged law­mak­ers from ob­ject­ing to the re­sults.</p>
    <p>Mr Trump has con­tin­ued to falsely claim that Mr Bi­den won the elec­tion be­cause of wide­spread voter fraud and has de­manded that con­gres­sional Repub­li­cans work to over­turn the re­sults.</p>
    <p>In a New Year’s Eve mes­sage posted on Twit­ter, he de­scribed his ac­com­plish­ments in of­fice as “his­toric vic­to­ries”.</p>
    <p>“We have to be re­mem­bered for what’s been done,” Mr Trump said.</p>
    <p>The Pres­i­dent, who was of­ten crit­i­cised for his cav­a­lier at­ti­tude to­wards the coro­n­avirus pan­demic, also re­marked that the US has pro­duced a Covid-19 vac­cine in record time and that he had cor­rectly pre­dicted it would come be­fore the year ended.</p>

